<div class="win-page">

<p>
  <strong>WhatCable for Windows</strong> is a clean-sheet rewrite of the macOS app for
  Windows 10 22H2 and Windows 11. It explains what each USB-C port is actually doing —
  link speed, charging state, and (on supported PCs) the power contract and cable
  e-marker — in plain English. It also adds a brand-new <strong>video-cable
  diagnostic</strong> for HDMI, DisplayPort, and USB-C-as-DisplayPort outputs that has
  no macOS equivalent.
</p>

<div class="win-cta">
  <a class="button accent" href="https://github.com/darrylmorley/whatcable/releases/latest">Download installer</a>
  <a class="button secondary" href="https://github.com/darrylmorley/whatcable/releases/latest">Get the MSIX package</a>
  <a class="button secondary" href="/cli">CLI docs</a>
</div>
<p class="win-cta-note">Free. Windows 10 22H2 or Windows 11 (widgets need Windows 11 22H2+). x64 &amp; ARM64. No driver install.</p>

<h2>What you get</h2>
<ul>
  <li><strong>Tray app.</strong> A system-tray popover that lists every USB-C port: what's plugged in, the negotiated link speed, the charging state, and — on UCSI-capable PCs — the power contract and decoded cable e-marker.</li>
  <li><strong>Video-cable diagnostic (new).</strong> For every HDMI / DisplayPort / USB-C-DP output it shows the connector, the active mode, the display's maximum capability, and a "what's limiting the link" verdict derived from EDID / CTA-861 / DisplayID.</li>
  <li><strong>Command-line tool.</strong> <code>whatcable-cli.exe</code> emits JSON that's schema-compatible with the macOS CLI, plus extra <code>video</code> and <code>thunderbolt</code> sections.</li>
  <li><strong>Windows 11 widgets.</strong> Small / medium / large Adaptive Card widgets for the Widgets Board and the lock screen.</li>
  <li><strong>Pro tier.</strong> Pin diagrams, a liquid-detection indicator, and a live system-wide Power Monitor graph, unlocked with an offline licence key.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Install</h2>
<h3>Installer (recommended)</h3>
<p>
  Download <code>WhatCable-Setup-&lt;version&gt;.exe</code> from the
  <a href="https://github.com/darrylmorley/whatcable/releases/latest">Releases page</a>
  and run it. It installs the tray app and the CLI, and adds a Start-menu entry.
  Launch-at-login is controlled inside the app under <strong>Settings → Launch at login</strong>.
</p>
<h3>MSIX package</h3>
<p>
  Prefer a packaged install? Download <code>WhatCable-&lt;version&gt;.msix</code>, double-click
  it, and confirm in the App Installer dialog. The MSIX is required for the Windows 11
  widgets, because they're registered through the package manifest. The package is
  code-signed; on a machine that doesn't yet trust the certificate, export the signing
  certificate as a Base-64 X.509 <code>.cer</code> from the package's digital-signature
  details and install it into <strong>Local Machine → Trusted People</strong> first.
</p>

<h2>What works on your hardware</h2>
<p>
  How much detail you see depends on your PC. A USB-C <strong>device list with negotiated
  speeds</strong> and the <strong>video diagnostic</strong> work everywhere. Power-delivery,
  e-marker, and pin-diagram detail need a <strong>UCSI-capable PC</strong> (most 2019-or-newer
  laptops). The full breakdown:
</p>

