<p>
  On a UCSI PC the <code>powerSources</code>, cable e-marker, and <code>pdCapable</code>
  fields are populated and <code>unavailable_reason</code> disappears. When a display's
  EDID can be read, the <code>video[].port</code> object gains <code>edidParsed</code> and
  <code>sinkMaxMode</code>, and <code>diagnostic.bottleneck</code> becomes a concrete
  verdict instead of <code>Unknown</code>. See the <a href="/cli">CLI docs</a> for more.
</p>

<h2>FAQ</h2>
<dl class="faq">
  <dt>Why no per-lane Thunderbolt speeds?</dt>
  <dd>
    There is no public Windows API that reports per-lane Thunderbolt link speeds. We
    enumerate the device chain via SetupAPI and label each entry honestly with
    <code>unavailable_reason: per_lane_speeds_unavailable_on_windows</code> rather than
    guessing. macOS exposes this through Apple-only IOKit services that Windows has no
    equivalent for.
  </dd>

  <dt>Why does PD / charger / cable info require a UCSI PC?</dt>
  <dd>
    Power-delivery contracts, charger PDOs, and cable e-marker data come from
    <strong>UCSI</strong> (USB Type-C Connector System Software Interface) — a firmware
    interface the PC's USB-C controller must expose. Most laptops from 2019 onwards have
    it; many desktops and older laptops don't. Without UCSI those rows show
    <code>ucsi_not_supported</code>. The USB device list and the video diagnostic don't
    rely on UCSI and work everywhere.
  </dd>

  <dt>The cable e-marker is blank even on a UCSI PC. Why?</dt>
  <dd>
    Windows only reads the e-marker after the controller negotiates above 3 A, so a
    low-wattage charger may never trigger the read. Try a higher-wattage USB-C charger.
  </dd>

  <dt>Why does the video diagnostic say "unable to determine"?</dt>
  <dd>
    That means the display's EDID couldn't be read — some virtual displays, KVMs, and
    capture devices don't expose one. The connector and active mode still show; the
    bottleneck verdict needs EDID / CTA-861 / DisplayID data.
  </dd>

  <dt>Where are the widgets?</dt>
  <dd>
    Widgets require Windows 11 22H2+ and the <strong>MSIX</strong> install, which
    registers the widget provider through the package manifest. The unpackaged installer
    build ships the tray app and CLI but not the widgets.
  </dd>

  <dt>Is it the same app as macOS?</dt>
  <dd>
    No — it's a clean-sheet WinUI 3 / C# rewrite, because the macOS app depends on
    Apple-only IOKit services with no Windows equivalent. It reuses the same data models,
    decoders, and JSON shape, so downstream tooling keeps working across platforms.
  </dd>
</dl>

